subSection.paragraph:
The Afrotropical region, in spite of being a diversity hotspot for large Branchiopoda (
Brendonck et al . 2008
; Rogers 2013;
Brendonck et al . 2015
), is the one of the most unexplored and under-sampled areas. The majority of studies of large Branchiopoda from Africa have been carried out in southern Africa ( South Africa , Namibia and Zimbabwe ), while the fauna of Anostraca from the rest of the continent is still poorly known ( Hamer & Brendonck 1997 ;
Brendonck et al . 2008
;
Nhiwatiwa et al . 2014
;
Nhiwatiwa et al . 2017
). Indeed,
Streptocephalus
has not been recorded in Central Africa yet. It has been reported that the great species diversity displayed in
Streptocephalus
was due to its African origin and posterior vicariant events during Gondwana fragmentation (
Daniels et al . 2004
). These geological processes may have led to the spread and diversification of
Streptocephalus
to other warm areas across Nearctic, Palearctic, African and Indo-Malayan regions (
Sanoamuang et al. 2000
, 2002 ;
Maeda-Martínez et al. 2005
;
Nhiwatiwa et al. 2017
;
Kappas et al. 2017
), but kept them out of Southern America, Antarctic, New Zealand and a wide area of Australia . These data lead to the assumption that the absence of records is likely caused by lack of exploration rather than being a real distribution pattern and that further new records of either described species and new taxa are yet to be discovered through Central Africa. Our results highlight the importance of exploration of under sampled areas and study phylogeographic patterns of fairy shrimps to detect and solve species complexes.
